It's all perfect BUT why are the exported data sooooo big? A 3 min. Song is about 40mb ... How do I create smaller data?
replyContent: Thanks for your feedback, Emrullah. All G-Stomper Producer exports uncompressed audio in .wav format (by default 16bit, 48kHz, Stereo). Wav is one of the state-of-the-art professional audio formats and gives you the best possible export quality. If you need smaller files, please use an audio converter app to convert the .wav to .mp3 for example.

content: I bought this during your sale to go alongside GStomper Studio that I bought last year, AWESOME ! I've got it on my S9+ 256gbs but what 10 inch tablet do you recommend to run this ? I had a Samsung Tab3 Lite but it was useless with little storage so am looking for a Budget to Mid Range tablet so what can you recommend ? Lenovo ? Samsung ? Also, Is there anywhere I can listen to your CHILL samples beats that you've got on sale for this PRIOR to buying ? Thanks, Music IS Life ! \m/ Stephanie :)
replyContent: Thanks a lot for your feedback, Stephanie. As tablet I'd go for a Samsung S3/S4 Tab or for a second hand pixel-c (second hand because it's no longer shipped). Or you could go for a chromebook, e.g. an Asus flip, or Acer have good chromebooks, too. Regarding the sample packs, there should be a preview link in the app description.

content: loving it

Great app! The ability to set variable timings for each sample track is great to build polyrhythms. The probability step conditions, micro step adjustments, and random velocity are good to get a more human feel. My favorite feature is the song arranger and the ability to edit while it is playing. Glad to see the integration with Ableton and use of Google Oboe for a higher performing music app on Android. Keep it up.
replyContent: Thank you very much, Brian, for your excellent and comprehensive feedback. Much appreciated:)
